Good. Before writing a single backend endpoint, let's freeze the architecture.

For **LLM Council V1**, your backend should have exactly one responsibility:

> Receive a message → build context → route to selected model → store everything.

Nothing more.

# Backend Architecture

```text
backend/

├── app/
│
├── routers/
│   ├── chat.py
│   ├── conversation.py
│   └── memory.py
│
├── services/
│   ├── context_builder.py
│   ├── memory_service.py
│   ├── conversation_service.py
│   └── openrouter_service.py
│
├── providers/
│   └── openrouter.py
│
├── models/
│   ├── conversation.py
│   ├── message.py
│   └── memory.py
│
├── db/
│   ├── database.py
│   └── schemas.py
│
├── utils/
│
├── main.py
├── requirements.txt
└── .env
```

---

# Database Design

### conversations

```sql
id
title
created_at
updated_at
```

Example:

```text
LLM Council Architecture
```

---

### messages

```sql
id
conversation_id
role
model
content
created_at
```

Example:

```text
role = user
model = null

role = assistant
model = gpt-4o
```

---

### memories

```sql
id
conversation_id
memory_type
content
importance
created_at
```

Example:

```text
memory_type = tech_stack

content = React + FastAPI
```

---

### summaries

```sql
id
conversation_id
summary
updated_at
```

Example:

```text
User is building LLM Council
Uses OpenRouter
Uses React + FastAPI
```

---

# Request Flow

User sends:

```text
@gpt explain transformers
```

Frontend:

```json
{
  "conversation_id": 1,
  "model": "gpt",
  "message": "explain transformers"
}
```

---

# Chat Router

```python
POST /chat
```

Receives request.

Then:

```text
Chat Router
↓
Conversation Service
↓
Context Builder
↓
OpenRouter Service
↓
Response
↓
Store Message
```

---

# Context Builder

Most important service.

Input:

```text
Conversation ID
Current Message
```

Builds:

```text
Conversation Summary

+
Relevant Memories

+
Last 20 Messages

+
Current Prompt
```

Returns:

```python
full_context
```

This service becomes the heart of the backend.

---

# OpenRouter Service

Single responsibility:

```python
send_message(
    model,
    context
)
```

Example:

```python
send_message(
    "openai/gpt-4o",
    context
)
```

Later:

```python
send_message(
    "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4",
    context
)
```

Everything goes through OpenRouter.

---

# Memory Service

V1:

```text
Store memories manually
```

Example:

User says:

```text
I am using React and FastAPI
```

Store:

```text
React + FastAPI
```

---

V2:

Automatic extraction.

Prompt:

```text
Extract important project facts.
```

LLM returns:

```json
[
 {
  "type":"tech_stack",
  "content":"React + FastAPI"
 }
]
```

Store automatically.

This is where the "shared memory" magic starts.

---

# Model Tagging Logic

Input:

```text
@gpt Explain transformers
```

Backend parses:

```python
model = "gpt"
message = "Explain transformers"
```

Route:

```python
GPT
```

---

Input:

```text
@claude Review GPT answer
```

Route:

```python
Claude
```

Very simple.

---

# Cross Model Review

This is the first advanced feature I'd build.

User:

```text
@gpt Design a startup
```

GPT responds.

Store response.

Later:

```text
@claude Critique GPT answer
```

Backend:

```text
Fetch GPT response
+
Conversation Context
↓
Send to Claude
```

Now models appear to collaborate.

Very impressive for relatively little code.

---

# API Endpoints

V1 only:

```python
POST /chat

GET /conversations

POST /conversation

GET /conversation/{id}

DELETE /conversation/{id}
```

That's enough.

Don't build 20 endpoints.

---

